          "body": "The first twenty-one verses of Numbers 15 are technical legislation supplementing the offering regulations of Leviticus. The graduated table of vv. 4-10 assigns specific quantities of grain offering and drink offering to specific animals: a lamb receives a quarter-hin of oil and a quarter-hin of wine; a ram receives a third-hin each; a bull receives a half-hin each. The proportionality is not arbitrary. Larger animals required larger supplementary offerings, binding the worshiper's material resources more substantially to the act of worship. The 'soothing aroma' refrain (vv. 3, 7, 10, 13, 14) appears five times in the unit, insisting that properly structured worship is worship God receives with pleasure — the anthropomorphic idiom drawn from Genesis 8:21 signals divine satisfaction with the prescribed offering. The dough offering of vv. 18-21 extends worship into domestic life: the first baking of dough from the land's grain is itself a sacred moment. Together these regulations translate theological monotheism into economic practice — the Giver of the land receives the firstfruits of the land's produce in every form, from herd and flock to the kitchen. The theologically decisive insertion is the alien-inclusion principle of vv. 13-16, stated three times in rapid succession. 'One statute for you and for the alien' (v. 15), 'one law and one ordinance' (v. 16) — the covenant community is defined covenantally, not ethnically. The ger who has settled among Israel and wishes to worship YHWH does so under identical legal terms. No separate class of worship exists for the foreigner who has joined himself to Israel. This anticipates the New Testament's dissolution of the Jew-Gentile distinction within the covenant community (Ephesians 2:11-22; Galatians 3:28)."
