          "title": "The taxonomy of sin — unintentional versus defiant — 15:22-31",
          "body": "The center of Numbers 15 is its most theologically important section: the distinction between sin committed through shegagah (inadvertence, error, ignorance) and sin committed 'with a high hand' (b'yad ramah, v. 30) — that is, defiantly, with full knowledge and deliberate contempt. This is not a distinction between minor and major sins on a moral scale. It is a distinction between sins for which the sacrificial system provides a remedy and sins for which it does not. Unintentional sin — whether congregational (vv. 24-26) or individual (vv. 27-29) — is covered by blood. The priest makes atonement (kipher), and the LORD grants forgiveness (salach). The word salach, used exclusively of divine forgiveness throughout the Hebrew Bible, appears three times in four verses (vv. 25, 26, 28), hammering home the chapter's good news: the God who prescribes the offering is the God who grants the pardon. Defiant sin, however, crosses a different line. The person who sins 'defiantly' is said in verse 30 to be 'blaspheming the LORD' (gadaph, to revile, to treat with contempt). Verse 31 gives the diagnosis: 'he has despised the word of the LORD and has broken His commandment.' The problem is not the act but the attitude — a knowing, intentional rejection of YHWH's authority. For this there is no prescribed sacrifice, no priestly intercession, no forgiveness formula. The sentence is 'completely cut off' (karat with the infinitive absolute for emphasis). The Epistle to the Hebrews draws on this same distinction in its warnings about 'willful sin' after receiving the knowledge of the truth (Hebrews 10:26-29) and about apostasy for which 'it is impossible to renew again to repentance' (Hebrews 6:4-6). The NT authors are reading Numbers 15 with theological precision."
