        "body": "The narrative of the unnamed sabbath-breaker functions as a legal case study placed immediately after the defiant-sin law — not accidentally but purposefully. The compiler of Numbers intends the reader to see the continuity: here is what b'yad ramah looks like when it encounters the covenant justice system.\n\nGathering wood on the Sabbath was not an act of ignorance. The Sabbath command had been given at Sinai with unambiguous clarity (Exodus 20:8-11) and supplemented with the death penalty (Exodus 31:14-15). The man found gathering wood was not operating in legal ambiguity — he was performing manual labor on the day explicitly set aside from labor. Whether the congregation's hesitation in verse 34 reflects uncertainty about the mode of execution (stoning versus another form of death) or some other procedural question, the LORD's verdict in verse 35 is unambiguous: 'The man shall surely be put to death.' The infinitive absolute (*mot yumat*, 'dying he shall die') is the grammar of legal certainty.\n\nTwo features of the execution carry theological weight. First, 'all the congregation shall stone him with stones' — the whole community is drawn into the act. The sabbath-breaker's sin was not a private transgression; it was a public act that threatened the covenant community's holiness before YHWH. The whole congregation's participation in the execution enacts the seriousness of that communal threat. This is not mob violence but covenantal solidarity in enforcing the boundary that separates the covenant community from covenant contempt.\n\nSecond, the execution takes place 'outside the camp.' The camp is the space of covenant fellowship, organized around the tabernacle at its center (Numbers 2). To be expelled outside the camp is to be expelled from the presence of YHWH, from the covenant community, from the sphere of sacred space. The place of execution is the place of excision — the geography enacts the legal verdict. Hebrews 13:11-13 meditates on exactly this geography: 'The bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy place by the high priest as an offering for sin are burned outside the camp. Therefore Jesus also, that He might sanctify the people through His own blood, suffered outside the gate.' The One who died in the place of the cut-off bore the covenant curse in the location that Numbers 15 established as the site of covenantal exclusion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mot yumat* — the doubled verb using the infinitive absolute is the OT's emphatic construction for the death penalty: 'he shall certainly be put to death.' *Ragam baavanim* (stoned with stones) — the specific means of execution signals community participation; each stone thrown is each member's covenantal affirmation of the verdict. *Chuts lamachaneh* (outside the camp) — the same phrase used for quarantining the leprous and the ritually unclean, making spatial exclusion the enacted form of covenant cutting-off."
